{
  "texts": [
    "Interactive music applications, on the other hand, typically use buffer-by-buffer processing and require a buffer size corresponding to 10 ms or less to fulfill the low-latency constraint for real-time interaction.",
    "Maintaining an RTF <1.0 with such small buffer sizes is a challenging constraint, as RTF values can be inversely correlated with buffer size Hayes et al. (2021).",
    "Computational complexity can also be measured by counting the number of floating-point operations required to synthesize one second of audio (FLOPS) (Liu et al., 2020; Tian et al., 2020; Watts et al., 2023).",
    "In theory, this provides a hardware agnostic measurement of computational complexity and provides fair method for comparing algorithms (Schwartz et al., 2020).",
    "However, running time does not always perfectly correlate with FLOPS; for instance, the parallelism provided by GPUs offers speedups for convolutional layers that are not possible on CPUs (Asperti et al., 2022)."
  ]
}